<div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation">
      <div id="res833234531" class="bucketwrap image large">
            <div class="imagewrap" data-crop-type="">
    <img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/13/gettyimages-154556004_wide-6dfdf023a64735ee0440f841873894ef5dc81b0f-s1100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/13/gettyimages-154556004_wide-6dfdf023a64735ee0440f841873894ef5dc81b0f-s1100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="A woman on a private plane holds champagne." />
        <div class="enlarge-options">
            <a class="enlargelink" href="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/13/gettyimages-154556004-e6a5b51cd26b8c3993064c956a4fe7ec2bdd1f04-s1200.jpg">Enlarge this image</a>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="credit-caption">
    <div class="caption-wrap">
        <div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption">
        </div>


    </div>

    <span class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
        
        Flashpop/Getty Images
        
    </span>
</div>
<div class="enlarge_measure">
    <div class="img_wrap">
        <img data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/13/gettyimages-154556004-e6a5b51cd26b8c3993064c956a4fe7ec2bdd1f04-s1200.jpg" alt="A woman on a private plane holds champagne." />
    </div>
</div>
<div class="enlarge_html">
    <div class="image_data">
        <span class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
            
            Flashpop/Getty Images
            
        </span>
    </div>
</div>
   </div>
   <p>COVID-19 attacks indiscriminately: Young or old, rich or poor, it seems like everyone is vulnerable to the virus. But <em>New York Times </em>economics writer Nelson Schwartz says increasing economic inequality in the U.S. means that, as a group, the country's wealthiest one percent are likely to fare better during the pandemic than everyone else.</p>   <p><em>"</em>One of the most striking aspects of the emergency of coronavirus is the inability to get tested," he notes. But Schwartz says that concierge doctors — primary care physicians who charge several thousands of dollars a month for access to care — have been able provide their patients with COVID-19 tests that might otherwise be impossible to obtain.</p>   <p>"One concierge doctor I spoke to rounded up viral swabs ahead of time," Schwartz says. "He was able to arrange testing for his clients when others couldn't get tests."</p>   <p>In addition to having <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-testing-elite.html">better access</a> to COVID-19 tests, Schwartz notes that the rich are more likely to have flexible private transportation services and second homes — which can ease the burden of "social distancing" to avoid the virus.</p>   <aside id="ad-backstage-wrap" aria-label="advertisement">
    

    <div id="ad-backstage-News_National" class="ad-backstage" data-ad-config='{"network":"\/6735\/","site":{"default":"n6735.NPR","mobile":"n6735.NPRMOBILE"},"zone":"News_National","targets":{"testserver":"false","isPodcastEpisode":"false","storyId":"833042757","program":"Fresh_Air","agg":["191676894"],"book_genres":["Nonfiction","History___Society","Business___Economy"]},"location":"backstage","deferred":false,"isBetweenContent":true,"isAggSponsorship":false,"borderClass":""}'></div>

</aside>   <div id="res833052097" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage823975440" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/31/823975440/as-pandemic-spreads-the-developing-world-looks-like-the-next-target"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/sections\/goatsandsoda\/2020\/03\/31\/823975440\/as-pandemic-spreads-the-developing-world-looks-like-the-next-target"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/30/india---cv---3-30-20_sq-ef329defa5acc8ad16170f05d093a24701ff1406-s100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/03/30/india---cv---3-30-20_sq-ef329defa5acc8ad16170f05d093a24701ff1406-s100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="As Pandemic Spreads, The Developing World Looks Like The Next Target" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/">Goats and Soda </a></h3>
            <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/31/823975440/as-pandemic-spreads-the-developing-world-looks-like-the-next-target"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/sections\/goatsandsoda\/2020\/03\/31\/823975440\/as-pandemic-spreads-the-developing-world-looks-like-the-next-target"}' >As Pandemic Spreads, The Developing World Looks Like The Next Target</a></h3>
         </div>
         
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKETBLOCK" -->
      </div>
      
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" -->
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES833052097" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " -->
   <p><em>"</em>People say we're all in it together. But to me, the pandemic has exposed these class differences," he says.</p>   <p>Schwartz's new book, <em>The Velvet Rope Economy</em>, examines how new services spare the super rich from the hassles of everyday life, including getting stuck in traffic, standing in line or waiting on hold. He notes that the ramifications of our stratified society run deep.</p>   <p>"I think the result is less sympathy, less empathy and a sort of a harder-edge society," Schwartz says. "There's a lot of anger among people who are not benefiting from these kind of privileges. ... There isn't a feeling that we're in it together. ... Instead it's each man for himself."</p>   <div class="hr"><hr></div>   <h3 class="edTag">Interview Highlights</h3>   <div id="res833042838" class="bucketwrap internallink internallink--book" previewtitle="Book Edition Information">
    <div id="res833042829" class="bucketwrap image book">
      <div class="imagewrap" data-crop-type="">
    <a href="/books/titles/833042780/the-velvet-rope-economy-how-inequality-became-big-business">
        <img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/bakertaylor/covers/t/the-velvet-rope-economy/9780385543088_custom-0fe3f44728fa7b1a5fe44eb5181b8023c4066f73-s1200-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/bakertaylor/covers/t/the-velvet-rope-economy/9780385543088_custom-0fe3f44728fa7b1a5fe44eb5181b8023c4066f73-s1200.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="The Velvet Rope Economy" />
    </a>
</div>
<div class="credit-caption">
    <div class="caption-wrap">
        <div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption">
        </div>


    </div>

